London Abram vivian
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 27: past. to which referre you, sence recd. yd of
19: ditto, by which am hertely sorry to understand all yd laces to be seased
yett hope you gott cleare with a lesser loss then you exspected of which
should be gladd to understand yd bill for £150:- p. in H Cole shall accept
& pay accordingly & pass to my acctt., I exspect to know how all the rest
of our goods be shipped, to governe my self according for I am informed
that northeen goods are some what afalling & verepleat y. & heregod
be thancke wee have had an indifferent good demand of late, which
made a good breach in our pariell & in case I did not exspect you over
thinck I should send a fresh order for more goods which I partely
delay till I see you inclosed returne yd bill for 201 crouwne, which
please to send imee indorsed & I shall endeavour to procure the needfull
I have given you creditt for my half share in the acctt of charges of mr
shiner, butt I never sace the like to make butt one same &to say for
all charges in all so much whithout any fuuther explication, is some
what to darck for mee, though I am contended if you be satiefyed
all our acctt. & sales will be ready god willing as soone as our greatet
hurgy of sale is past & so remaine with hinde saluts
@8 ditto
London John Loyd
h
Sr. I have wrott to you on the 17: past some fewlines, sence non from
you though I do mich wish to do you any service, & that wee might
have alarger correspondency toghether towards, which nothing should
bewanting on my side: I do beleave that English butter will be agood
com. here next winter, as also the frith of yoches & bellifap because she is vere much
is en here, & by all apearence will be vere deare. This finther & cheefly to advise you
how m. moore alias norton after 3 a 4 dayes sichrets dyed in his prison in our towim
rasble, & so poone, that a certaine engles man gare a crowne to gett him burried,
for as long he lived he did do him self will with is pretended wife, pich is kept
att is lodging a frisoner to pay his & her expences, for the time of is haveing bee
there, wich as I am informed is about £50- & the people suposeing to have
a great yintleman in their house finde nothing now, so itt will be a great loss
to them, Intrim I supote his tane. wife will be contented with hen fortiune &
I wish her a truer husband. which is the needfell, att present from
a 8 ditto
London m. Henry Maijnard
My last to you was on the 25 past, sence non from you, in the ineom vahile our
goods ane all come to handes except the bale N. 43 which is well arrived at Bruges.
& of the fijne cloates are sold, they prove deare & so doth all watt of late I receaved
principally the redds, which I doubt will never sell to proffitt, for never I saw dearer goods
besides they have been opened a board of warner, & so mishandled, as if they had leim
seven jeare in a ware house, besides one aurora al most spoiled with spats of dust &
mudd, I wonder you suld should take no more notice of what formerly I wrott you
do exparss in y bill of loadings to open no goods with a pennaltie, & whiy do you not send
the bills of loading to mee dixcetely, for what hath coots to do with them, for he s tofoll
mij onder, & in case he doth not procure satisfaction for the like abuses I'll imploy
them that will do stt. I have no pack whites by mee so please to advise mee how
the P.F. ylallow, & NW ronge manck doth sill & if no apearence of falling: pay
hasten forward the cottons: Intrim itt 3eems as if the dray cullours were out of fashion
here, & all the demand falls upon darck browne mushes according, to the inclosed fatt.
in wwich all kinde of reddisch must be avoided, & am desired to write for 4 or 5 quarts
of pure good goods of the inclosed patt. of 12 to 15 ƒ a yd., so could wish you could
dispatch them with all eares imaginable, & because the haste for the same is greatt
somy freind disired mee to lett them come by way of doven & newpont by the pacquet boat
which I desire you to do, exceps a restes was ready to depast for ostend as to one as these 4 a
5 oIshall be ready, which might bewrapped with a white hertre of 22 yd. to make itt the
lighten in which I hope you will take all Imaginable care to advance the super fine
goods, as well as low prijses in sale: I expect that the blews & mocks are sint forward
by this time. inclised you have my bill for £200 - att 2110 on m. Will. Scawen att
35„4 for yo acctt. mr. furnase his freind att Brussel hath nort yett disposed of the in ordered
mony, so that I can not exactely advise you how much to pass to acctt, m. Eokhoven
for the heirts of made. Bouwens hath told mee you would please to draw the neet ballance
due to you, on hun att sight p lass, & that he shall punitualy pay itt, which is the needfull
att present from
a 8 oct. 1681
Londen m. Will Scawen
mij last to you was on the 27th past, to which please to be referred, sence non from you,
inclosed you have the invoyce of 178¼ of tyke in 2 severall balot of which each doth
cont. 5 duble pecces viz the 2 seales, & great lead the bale N. 20, is in goodnese some
what epcceding N.19, for the tykes in N. 20 are the vere best that everwere sent to England
a yd gev. I have this day drawne on you £200- s att 2 vr payable to the ord. of m maynand
att 35. & which please to accept, & pass to yd acctt., the rest shall finde itt self on the
same acctt on which I did not exspect should have been so long in disbins, because I thought
that our callicoes trade should have been quicker, & great part is yett unsold, nevertheless I
le do my ende avour with the goods ass well as I can, whilst I long to know how the sale
hath been with you httt att the lastendre comp. In case you have bought what I noted, you
will finde the valeuw for my share on my acctt., so do exspect no draught from you,
hope my pacquitt N. 3 of laces is with you by this time of which should be ghadd to
understand, I hope N.4. will be with you vere speedly
Crremrandum for m. Scawen to send the long cloth so asthey are sold hutt itt
will not be a mis in case you putt in each bale some salempords white as the last
time you did putt in the dungarees

monsr. volgens ul mij hadde gelooft, soo hadde ick ontrent Panus het restrende
gelt vande in lantsche lakens verwaght, oversulx ick bidde ul manqueert
niet dat te senden, opdat wij met goede irtelligentie mogen continueeren
inonse correspondentie, want ick het wort van een eerlijk man betrouw
ende mij daer op verlate soo sien dan het salve te gemoet alsoo ick
oock den uetsteten comgelt verlegen ben. het gelt vande stadt
alhier hebbe noch niet ontfangen sal daer even wel mijn best
